{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Intelligent cinematography (IC) leverages artificial intelligence (AI) to assist camera-based tasks throughout the media production workflow.",
    "For pre-production, this concerns shot planning, for example using a script (Riedl et al. 2010; Dhahir et al. 2021) or user input (Christianson et al. 1996; Wu and Christie 2016).",
    "For production, this includes automated camera-control (Lim and Sinha 2015; Coaguila et al. 2016; Mademlis et al. 2019c; Bonatti et al. 2020; Yan et al. 2022), methods for content acquisition (Mildenhall et al. 2021; Pumarola et al. 2021; Zhao et al. 2022; LeGendre et al. 2022) and assisting directors and camera operators (Drucker and Zeltzer 1995; de Lima et al. 2009; Hu 2021; Hossain and Little 2018; Cao et al. 2017; Bridgeman et al. 2019).",
    "For post-production, this involves in-camera virtual effects (ICVFX) (Sharma 2021; Kavakli and Cremona 2022; Finance and Zwerman 2015; Okun and Susan Zwerman 2020), dealing with camera artefacts such as reflections (Wu et al. 2022a), de-rigging and novel viewpoint synthesis (Kerbl et al. 2023; Mildenhall et al. 2021; Yu et al. 2021).",
    "Intelligent cinematography influences the worlds of cinema, gaming and televised broadcasting and streaming."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For pre-production, this concerns shot planning, for example using a script (Riedl et al. 2010; Dhahir et al. 2021) or user input (Christianson et al. 1996; Wu and Christie 2016).",
